(V.  ENERGY\015)'
(\015)'
(\015)'
(     1.  Sun Tzu said:  The control of a large force is the same\015)'
(principle as the control of a few men:  it is merely a question\015)'
(of dividing up their numbers.\015)'
(\015)'
(     [That is,  cutting up the army into regiments,  companies,\015)'
(etc.,  with subordinate officers in command of each.  Tu Mu\015)'
(reminds us of Han Hsin's famous reply to the first Han Emperor,\015)'
(who once said to him:  "How large an army do you think I could\015)'
(lead?"   "Not more than 100,000 men, your Majesty."   "And you?"\015)'
(asked the Emperor.  "Oh!" he answered, "the more the better."]\015)'
(\015)'
(     2.  Fighting with a large army under your command is nowise\015)'
(different from fighting with a small one:   it is merely a\015)'
(question of instituting signs and signals.\015)'
(     3.  To ensure that your whole host may withstand the brunt\015)'
(of the enemy's attack and remain unshaken - this is effected by\015)'
(maneuvers direct and indirect.\015)'
(\015)'
(     [We now come to one of the most interesting parts of Sun\015)'
(Tzu's treatise, the discussion of the CHENG and the CH`I."  As it\015)'
(is by no means easy to grasp the full significance of these two\015)'
(terms,   or   to render them consistently by   good   English\015)'
(equivalents;  it may be as well to tabulate some of   the\015)'
(commentators'  remarks on the subject before proceeding further.\015)'
(Li Ch`uan:  "Facing the enemy is CHENG, making lateral diversion\015)'
(is CH`I.  Chia Lin:  "In presence of the enemy,  your troops\015)'
(should be arrayed in normal fashion, but in order to secure\015)'
(victory abnormal maneuvers must be employed."   Mei Yao-ch`en:\015)'
("CH`I is active, CHENG is passive; passivity means waiting for an\015)'
(opportunity, activity beings the victory itself."  Ho Shih:   "We\015)'
(must cause the enemy to regard our straightforward attack as one\015)'
(that is secretly designed, and vice versa; thus CHENG may also be\015)'
(CH`I,  and CH`I may also be CHENG."  He instances the famous\015)'
(exploit of Han Hsin, who when marching ostensibly against Lin-\015)'
(chin \(now Chao-i in Shensi\), suddenly threw a large force across\015)'
(the Yellow River in wooden tubs,  utterly disconcerting his\015)'
(opponent. [Ch`ien Han Shu, ch. 3.]  Here, we are told, the march\015)'
(on Lin-chin was CHENG, and the surprise maneuver was CH`I."\015)'
